        "text": "Churchill at the Treasury : Remaking Conservative Taxation Policy, 1924-29\n\nThe First World War marked a major transformation in the claims of governments on taxpayers throughout Europe, and the problems which emerged were central to the postwar problems of political and social stabilisation ('). In Britain, the war resulted in an upward shift in total public expenditure as a share of gross domestic product from 11.9 per cent in 1913 to 23.6 per cent in 1924, at which level it remained until the outbreak of the Second World War(2). Not only did the weight of taxation increase, but there was also a further shift towards direct taxation on income and profits and away from indirect taxation on consumption. The trend of the previous seventy or eighty years was continued, and Britain became still more divergent from the norm in the rest of Europe. In 1913/14, direct taxes amounted to 57.5 per cent of government revenues; by 1919/20, the proportion was 75.1 per cent, and it still stood at 66.9 per cent in 1924/5(3).\n\nThe tax system became much more progressive, continuing the trend started by the introduction of graduated death duties in 1894 and a graduated income tax in 1909. In 1913/14, the level of income tax on \"earned\" incomes received by married men with two children rose from 0.1 per cent on an income of £150 (the point at which liability started) to 2.7 per cent on £500, and a maximum of 8.3 per cent on £50,000. \"Unearned\" or investment income paid more, as a result both of a higher rate of income tax and the burden of death duties : the combined impact of these direct taxes amounted to 0.1 per cent, 6.8 per cent and 18.0 per cent respectively. At the end of the"
